1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,307
Some websites are impossible to avoid: government forms, university portals, and health directories.

2
00:00:05,307 --> 00:00:10,296
When one is confusing or missing a feature, you normally have to wait for the owner to fix it.

3
00:00:10,296 --> 00:00:16,506
OpenPatch gives users another option: safely repair the website for themselves, then share that repair with everyone.

4
00:00:16,506 --> 00:00:18,028
Here is the whole product.

5
00:00:18,028 --> 00:00:20,721
One person tells Codex what the website needs.

6
00:00:20,721 --> 00:00:24,408
Codex inspects the page and creates a small, constrained patch.

7
00:00:24,408 --> 00:00:27,804
OpenPatch tests it and publishes it for that exact domain.

8
00:00:27,804 --> 00:00:33,423
Everyone else installs the repair without using AI, creating an account, or entering an API key.

9
00:00:33,423 --> 00:00:35,700
Take this fictional MetroCare directory.

10
00:00:35,700 --> 00:00:40,084
It has twelve useful providers, but no search, no filters, and no comparison.

11
00:00:40,084 --> 00:00:47,143
A patient looking for wheelchair access, Urdu support, and a clinic accepting new patients must open and inspect every card.

12
00:00:47,143 --> 00:00:49,989
The website works, but it still fails that person.

13
00:00:49,989 --> 00:00:55,360
The user describes the problem in OpenPatch and copies a privacy-safe Repair Brief into Codex.

14
00:00:55,360 --> 00:01:02,788
The brief contains page structure and selector candidates, never form values, cookies, storage, private page text, or URL queries.

15
00:01:02,788 --> 00:01:09,645
Codex then uses the OpenPatch authoring skill to inspect the page, choose approved building blocks, and test the result.

16
00:01:09,645 --> 00:01:11,951
This is not an arbitrary userscript.

17
00:01:11,951 --> 00:01:19,895
A patch can request safe operations such as layout repair, accessibility, local autosave, search, filtering, and comparison.

18
00:01:19,895 --> 00:01:24,892
It cannot contain JavaScript, HTML templates, network calls, or cookie access.

19
00:01:24,892 --> 00:01:29,376
Here the patch applies eleven operations, and every target is healthy.

20
00:01:29,376 --> 00:01:32,487
The missing controls now appear directly inside MetroCare.

21
00:01:32,487 --> 00:01:35,760
I choose wheelchair access, Urdu, and accepting new patients.

22
00:01:35,760 --> 00:01:38,495
Twelve services immediately become one clear match.

23
00:01:38,495 --> 00:01:45,952
The preferences stay on this device, result changes are announced for assistive technology, and these interactions send no network request.

24
00:01:45,952 --> 00:01:48,260
OpenPatch can add real product capability.

25
00:01:48,260 --> 00:01:53,261
I clear the filters, select two providers, and open a keyboard-accessible comparison table.

26
00:01:53,261 --> 00:01:57,932
The trusted runtime builds this table only from fields the patch declared in advance.

27
00:01:57,932 --> 00:02:02,108
Nothing is scraped from arbitrary page text, and nothing leaves the browser.

28
00:02:02,108 --> 00:02:07,263
After one person authors the repair, everyone else gets a normal extension experience.

29
00:02:07,263 --> 00:02:18,053
OpenPatch finds the matching community patch, shows the exact website scope, permissions, version, SHA-256 receipt, scheduled compatibility result, and a fresh live selector check.

30
00:02:18,053 --> 00:02:19,372
One click installs it.

31
00:02:19,372 --> 00:02:22,849
AI was needed once; every later user needs only the patch.

32
00:02:22,849 --> 00:02:28,489
Websites change, so the Compatibility Sentinel checks every published repair in Chromium every six hours.

33
00:02:28,489 --> 00:02:32,787
If a selector breaks, the patch is quarantined before another user discovers it.

34
00:02:32,787 --> 00:02:38,319
The same safe engine can repair a mobile form, preserve unfinished progress, and add accessible errors.

35
00:02:38,319 --> 00:02:43,530
OpenPatch is a public feature layer for the web: when the owner will not fix it, users still can.
